ultural change. Recasting well-known favorites from classic French fairy tales, as well as Arthurian legends and English and German tales, the updated interpretations in this collection allow for more perverse settings and disillusioned perspectives—a trademark style and ethos of the decadent tradition.In these stories, characters puncture the optimism of the naive, talismans don't work, and the most deserving don’t always get the best rewards. The fairies are commonly victims of modern cynicism and technological advancement, but just as often are dangerous creatures corrupted by contemporary society. The collection underlines such decadent themes as the decline of civilization, the degeneration of magic and the unreal, gender confusion, and the incursion of the industrial. The volume editors provide an informative introduction, biographical notes for each author, and explanatory notes throughout.Subverting the conventions of the traditional fairy tale, these old tales made new will entertain and startle even the most disenchanted readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAlbert Mockel.  aAlphonse Daudet.  aBeauty and the Beast.  aBelle Époque.  aBlue Beard.  aBrothers Grimm.  aCatulle Mendès.  aCharles Perrault.  aClaude Cahun.  aEmile Bergerat.  aFlowers of Evil.  aFélicien Rop.  aHansel and Gretel.  aHenri de Régnier.  aHenry Gauthier-Villars.  aJ-K Huysmans.  aJacques d’Adelswärd-Fersen.  aJean Lorrain.  aJules Lemaître.  aJules Ricard.  aLes Diaboliques.  aLes Fleurs du mal.  aLes Sataniques.  aMadame d’Aulnoy.  aMarcel Schwob.  aPaul Arène.  aPierre Veber.  aRachilde.  aRenée Vivien.  aRumpelstiltskin.  aThe Tinderbox.  aThe Valiant Tailor.  aThree Billy Goats Gruff.  aWilly.  afin de siècle.1 aSchultz, 